<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 802.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 24 1989 n535 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Info systems boom; federal needs may pick up DOD slack.andO;(Department of Defense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Projections at the first Electronic Industries Association (EIA)federal information systems conference in Washington, DC portraygrowing federal information systems needs by defense and civilianagencies.andP;  The military information systems market should grow 2to 3 percent yearly to about $9.5 billion in 1994, while thecivilian market will grow 3 to 5 percent yearly to $9.8 billion.andO;Major equipment upgrades, more comprehensive contracts, increasinguse of off-the-shelf equipment and open systems, and more pricecompetitiveness are among the identified federal informationsystem trends.andP;  Specific programs forthcoming in the next fewyears were identified for: each military agency, civilianagencies, NASA, the various executive departments, and the GeneralServices Administration.andP;  Systems contractors were exhorted to befamiliar with three Pentagon-wide initiatives.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EIAConferencesMarket AnalysisNational GovernmentTrendsExpendituresInformation Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Federal information systems markets. (graph)Projected U.S. sales. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>